description: From dun (“dusky brown”) +‎ -y (“forming adjectives of lesser degree”).
Probably from dun (“to ring”) +‎ -y (“forming adjectives of lesser degree”).

entries.meaning: (UK dialect) Somewhat deaf, hard of hearing.
(UK dialect, derogatory euphemistic) Slow to answer: stupid, unintelligent.
examples: What the devil are you dunny? won't you give me no answer?

entries.meaning: (UK dialect, derogatory euphemistic, obsolete) A dummy, an unintelligent person.
examples: Should a School-boy do so, he'd be whip'd for a Dunny.

description: A clipped form of English cant dunnakin (“outhouse”) + -y (“forming affectionate diminutives”). Dunnakin, dunnekin, etc. are of uncertain etymology, but probably from some form of English cant danna (“shit”) + ken (“pejorative slang for house”). The Scottish and North English senses may derive from Etymology 4 below, either under influence from English cant or as its original source.

entries.meaning: (UK slang, obsolete) Alternative form of danna: shit. [From 1859.]
(Australia and New Zealand slang, also dated Scotland and Northern England) An outhouse: an outbuilding used as a lavatory. [From 1933.]
examples: ‘Until you wake up to yourself, you can live in the old dunny for all I care.’

entries.meaning: (Australia and New Zealand slang) Any other place or fixture used for urination and defecation: a latrine; a lavatory; a toilet.
(Scotland, Northern England, slang, dated) A passageway, particularly those connecting an outhouse to the main building.

description: A clipped form of English dungeon + -y (“forming affectionate diminutives”).

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Northern England, slang, dated) A cellar, basement, or underground passage.
